\maketitle
Remember $k_n = n \frac{2\pi}{Na}$, and $-\pi/a \leq k < \pi/a$. Hence, $\Delta k = \frac{2\pi}{Na}$. So:
\begin{equation}
E_0 = \frac{1}{2}\sum_k \hbar \omega(k) = \frac{1}{2}\frac{1}{\Delta k}\sum_k \hbar \omega(k)\Delta k \to \frac{1}{2}\frac{1}{\Delta k}\int_{-\pi/a}^{\pi/a} \hbar \omega(k) dk = \frac{1}{2}\frac{Na}{2\pi}\int_{-\pi/a}^{\pi/a} \hbar \omega(k) dk. 
\end{equation}
This is the standard approach of replacing a discrete sum with an integral. It is allowed to do as long as the function we integrate varies slowly over $\Delta k$. This is obtained for $N \gg 1$. 

